			<tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"><span style="color: blue">Edited for easy reading:
<br />

<br />
It's probably easiest if I break these down into separate categories the 
<br />
same way you did: 
<br />

<br />
I hope that answers most of your questions. I wouldn't mind putting this 
<br />
conversation up on the mage board if you're cool with it. Either you or I 
<br />
can post it if you like. 
<br />

<br />
-Ryan </span>
<br />

<br />

<br />
Rytan, 
<br />

<br />
Hello, must be getting frazzled by this time I am sure so I will cut through 
<br />
the happy happy stuff and be concise. I just wanted to bring a few things 
<br />
up regarding GoD and more specifically mages withing GoD. 
<br />

<br />
First, mages main focus is offense. We sacrifice -all- defense in order to 
<br />
be what -should- be the most damaging offensive caster in game. In fact our 
<br />
offense really becomes our defense (the pet) and this is even more 
<br />
pronounced with the new AA for Shared Health. Between nukes and the pet we 
<br />
should be in the top 3 of dmg dealing on any fight over 1 minute in length. 
<br />
Our problems have been somewhat complex due to this dual nature of our 
<br />
offense. 
<br />

<br />
In order to be more accurate in what, if anything mages need in the 
<br />
offensive department we need some tools to be better guage ourselves. Here 
<br />
are some small things I think would be of great help to you as developers 
<br />
wondering what to do with the class and to us as players. 
<br />

<br />
Information Gathering Suggestions 
<br />

<br />
1) Pet Proc damage should be reported to the pet owner 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">1) Sounds good, I'll see if we can get that in. </span>
<br />

<br />
2) Make Pet Proc damage have its own filter so it can be separated from all 
<br />
other spell spam 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">2) Same (As 1)</span>
<br />

<br />
3) Give base HP/AC/Stats for base pets...this may not be something you wish 
<br />
to actually do but it would make for more complete analysis 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">3) Not sure how I feel about that, although I will probably be posting 
<br />
relative numbers for the different pets sometime in the future.</span>
<br />

<br />
Pet Offensive Suggestions 
<br />

<br />
1) The AA's are great but somewhat limited, we could leave the AA's as is 
<br />
but add in a base 10% boost to pet offensive ability for pets level 60 and 
<br />
up. Alternativly we could increase the percentage the AA grants up to 10% / 
<br />
15% / 20% instead of the current maximum of 10%. 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">1) I agree they need a post, but I'd say they mostly need a boost in the 
<br />
form of more dramatic upgrades via the pet foci, and a small increase in 
<br />
certain pets innately.</span> 
<br />

<br />
2) Pets are elemental in nature, they are attuned to thier element and 
<br />
should be highly unresistable in thier elemental damage procs, add a 
<br />
negative resist modifier to all 60 and up pet damage procs. There is 
<br />
already precedent for this with the Rathe Son elemental attack. 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">2) Sounds reasonable, I'll take a look at that as part of the pet changes 
<br />
I'm hoping to get in sometime in the next month after Gates ships. </span>
<br />

<br />
3) Add a new AA which grats the pet the ability to land critical procs just 
<br />
like melee PC's. The % chance to crit should equal the pet owners % chance 
<br />
to crit (So magicians with SCF 3 and FoM 3 for 30 AA points will have a pet 
<br />
that can crit 14% of the time). Thus giving incentive to boost both pet and 
<br />
owner power at the same time. 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">3) Pet crit procs sound ok, although I'm not sure how I'd want to implement 
<br />
it. Probably another set of AAs </span>
<br />

<br />

<br />
Pet Defensive Suggestions 
<br />

<br />
1) Pets need an innate defensive boost to level 60 and up pets. They should 
<br />
last longer than 10-12 seconds against a Tier two PoP mob. With a GM 
<br />
assiting I was set up with a Jord Militis in the arena. This mob was not 
<br />
changed in any way from the BoT version except it was rooted and would not 
<br />
summon. I tested all current pets 3 times with each of the following 
<br />
combinations and maximum new AA's: 
<br />
Newly summoned with BO5 
<br />
Newly summoned with BO5, Muzzle (10% Haste) Belt (500hp) and 
<br />
summoned proc 
<br />
weapons 
<br />
Newly summoned with BO5, Muzzle (10% Haste) Belt (500hp) and 
<br />
summoned proc 
<br />
weapons, and summoned plate armor 
<br />

<br />
The average pet lasted (with enrage) about 17-20 seconds. Better but still 
<br />
woeful, an additional base increase of 10% damage mitigation would put this 
<br />
pet right around the 27 second or so mark vs this level of mob. This is 
<br />
enough to be useful without overpowering. 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">1) I agree with this as well, and I've already done a lot of work on 
<br />
comparisons between the different pets mitigation values compared to each 
<br />
other and PCs of various equipment qualities. Again, I think it's best if 
<br />
this is granted as part of the increase from pet foci and some minor 
<br />
adjustments to the base pets abilities. Foci should also be more readily 
<br />
available, although perhaps more specific. Possibly bring back the 
<br />
elemental type foci or a defensive foci only. There's several ways to go 
<br />
with this. </span>
<br />

<br />
2) Put the level 60 pets on the same damage mitigation table as a 65 
<br />
warrior, pets should have the same defensive maxes as the 65 warrior. Why 
<br />
isn't this overpowering? Well frankly if there is another PC around with 
<br />
the way pets work the pet wont be tanking anything anyway except perhaps AE 
<br />
melee attacks. This is so the pet can live and do the damage it was 
<br />
intended to without sucking all our mana requiring the really low end heals 
<br />
we have. 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">2) I don't think this is really a good alternative, as the 5% mitigation 
<br />
bonus that warriors get is part of their class distinction and should be 
<br />
maintained. I do agree that pets need an increase in mitigation over all 
<br />
though. </span>
<br />

<br />
3) Pet Lay on Hands AA (Mend companion) heals 2146 HP at level 65. Change 
<br />
this to be a true lay hands ability and CH the pet. The 2146 figure does 
<br />
less than half of a focused Rathe's Son HP. 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">3) Sounds reasonable, but I'm hesitant to make this a complete CH for every 
<br />
pet for the rest of time. Maybe something like 6k, with future AAs to 
<br />
increase the amount healed as pet HP scale up more. </span>
<br />

<br />
4) Another AA perhaps instead of an innate defensive adjustment that allows 
<br />
magicians to train AA's for Pet Combat Stability and Pet Combat Agility. 
<br />
Basically with defensive AA's given to the masses, allow mages to train 
<br />
these for both themselves and thier pet. If you want to make mages really 
<br />
happy for a while and hopefully quit squacking for a bit make a retro change 
<br />
so that as the mage gains CA and CS AA's they are automatically applied to 
<br />
pets that mage summons as well. You could also make it a separate AA and 
<br />
charge more, obviously I would prefer the former =P 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">4) Not sure how I feel about this, although adding future AAs is possible. </span>
<br />

<br />
5) The MS pet, frankly I never used that line of pet anyway. I always 
<br />
thought of it as a novelty and not worth using. While I would like to see a 
<br />
useful one I would prefer that the base pets become the assortment of tools 
<br />
they were intended to be. 
<br />
<span style="color: blue">5) After talking to several mages in beta, the best way to go for the MS pet 
<br />
is a raid oriented pet that has some inherent abilities that make it easier 
<br />
to upkeep against AEs. Right now the pet is slated to have a mini-Calliav 
<br />
type ability that it can cast on it self every ~45 seconds. This is a 
<br />
relatively new addition and will probably be adjusted over the next few 
<br />
days.</span>
<br />

<br />

<br />
Hope that gives ou some ideas, I appreciate the opportunity to discuss this 
<br />
with you further. 
<br />

<br />
Thanks
<br />
Jaytee Bushwacker <Fires of Heaven>
<br />

<br />
Reply by Rytan to this thread for easy access:
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Quote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">Thanks for writing up those questions and posting the whole thing Jaytee, much appreciated. 
<br />

<br />
Asking for any abilities specifically aimed at soloing is going to be a hard sell for me, as I don't think soloing should be an equally lucrative way of gaining experience compared to grouping. Most of the problems I'm seeing brought up all come from the same basic problem. Mage pets don't scale correctly when compared to other parts of the game. You can't really compare pets directly to NPCs because player power doesn't scale directly against NPC power. For example, a level 40 warrior might be able to solo a level 40 kobold in Sol B, but there's no way he/she is going to solo a level 65 NPC. Likewise, I'm not going to create a pet that can tank better then a PC tank class. I think most of you can agree that a pet that can stand toe to toe with a Plane of Fire mob that walks over a warrior isn't appropriate for game balance. In my opinion the problem is that pets aren't scaling correctly next to different levels of equipment available in game. The basic % increases for different tiers of equipment need to be roughly the same for a PC as it is for pets. That's why I think improvements through pet foci makes the most sense. 
<br />

<br />
The MS IV pet isn't going to be ONLY a raid pet, but it's abilities are targeted at making it especially useful on raids. I think the roles that are assigned to the existing 4 elemental pets give mages the tools the need for group situations. Even if they aren't exactly where they need to be balance wise, they're at least aimed at the right targets. 
<br />
A quick break down on the MS IV pet: 
<br />
Higher damage then an air pet, but less then water w/backstabs. 
<br />
Lower melee mitigation 
<br />
Higher HP then the earth pet 
<br />
Innately casts Prism skin which is an absorb hit for 1 that stacks with the Calliav series, and Bull rush, which is similar to the air pet stun. 
<br />

<br />
Basically, in most raid situations the pet isn't going to be taking direct melee damage, but will probably be taking more from AEs and possibly rampage. Prism skin should absorb most hits as long as they come somewhat infrequently. Stack Calliav on this and you're not going to be taking very much damage at all from indirect hits, so you won't have to try very hard to keep this pet alive. Especially if you pick up pet affinity and get the benefit of group heals and MGB Paragon etc. Obviously the pet staying alive longer means you get more damage out of it, which is always a good thing. 
<br />

<br />
-Ryan</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" align="left"><tr><td><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=26797"><img src="http://www.jtbates.net/everquest/images/jtshieldtransparent.gif" border="0" /></a></td><td><a href="http://www.fohguild.org">[Fires of Heaven]</a> - <a href="http://forum.magecompendium.com/tower/viewtopic.php?t=3239">[Magician's Tower Library]</a></td></tr><tr><span style="font-size: 12px; line-height: normal"><span style="font-weight: bold">Join us in serverwide.magicians:fluffy</span></span></tr></table><br>
